{
  "answer": "In *Manusmṛti* Book 7, the source of the king's authority is most directly stated as divine in origin and self-sanctioning through *daṇḍa* (the rod of punishment), which is equated with *dharma* itself and protects the cosmic order.[^1]\n\nIn Fichte's *Zurückforderung der Denkfreiheit*, the source of the prince's authority is most directly stated as deriving from a voluntary transfer of society's executive power via social contract; the prince is thus bound to protect rights (including those of reason) rather than commanding them absolutely.[^2]\n\nManu's king would be more dangerous to defy. His *daṇḍa* is an autonomous, deity-like force that upholds all *varṇas* and *āśramas* through inherent, unyielding *dharma*; to oppose it risks not just earthly retribution but cosmic disorder, as even gods and worlds submit to it.[^3] Fichte's prince, by contrast, holds delegated, conditional power that subjects may reclaim if it violates reason or rights, rendering defiance a moral imperative rather than existential peril.[^4]\n\n[^1]: *Manusmṛti*, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/#p-73f910), [](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/#p-48dedc), and [](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/#p-96ec46).\n\n[^2]: *Zurückforderung der Denkfreiheit von den Fürsten Europens*, [paragraphs](/works/johann-gottlieb-fichte-zuruckforderung-der-denkfreiheit-bookde/02/translation/#p-ff7538) and [](/works/johann-gottlieb-fichte-zuruckforderung-der-denkfreiheit-bookde/02/translation/#p-be3fae).\n\n[^3]: *Manusmṛti*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/#p-1b8f43).\n\n[^4]: *Zurückforderung der Denkfreiheit von den Fürsten Europens*, [paragraph](/works/johann-gottlieb-fichte-zuruckforderung-der-denkfreiheit-bookde/01/translation/#p-657cba).",
